====Usage notes====
* Examples:
** The English word ''[[actual]]'' means real, but in many languages (e.g. French, Italian and Spanish, with varied spellings) it means ''[[current]]''.
** In English ''[[benzene]]'' refers to a specific chemical, C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>6</sub>, but in many languages (e.g. Dutch, Polish) it means ''[[gasolene]]/[[petrol]]''.
** The French verb ''[[demander]]'' means "''to [[ask]]''", but to English-speakers it sounds like "''to [[demand]]''", which could turn negotiation into confrontation.
** The Spanish adjective ''[[embarazado]]'' (more often used in the feminine form, ''[[embarazada]]'') means ''[[pregnant]]'', not ''[[embarrassed]]'' &mdash; "''estoy embarazada''" means "''I am pregnant''", not "''I am embarrassed''".
** The Spanish verb ''[[molestar]]'' means ''"to [[annoy]]"'', not ''"to [[molest]]"''. Similarly, the Italian verb ''[[molestare]]'' means "''to annoy''".
** The German verb ''[[will]]'' means "''to [[want]]''", and is not a future tense marker &mdash; "''Ich will gehen''" means "''I want to go''", not "''I will go''". Similarly, the word ''[[wil]]'' in Dutch and Afrikaans means "''to want''": "''Ik wil gaan''" (Dutch) and "''Ek wil gaan''" (Afrikaans) mean "''I want to go''". (although, to be more accurate, English ''[[will]]'', German ''[[will]]'' and Dutch and Afrikaans ''[[wil]]'' are actually only [[partial false friend|partial false friends]], because ''will'' does occasionally have the same [or a very similar] meaning in English as in German, such as in the phrase "If you will it to be so", or in "God willing").
** The Italian adjective ''[[triviale]]'' means ''[[vulgar]]'', not ''[[trivial]]'', though the two words do share a common Latin root (''[[trivium]]'' that in Latin means [[crossroad]]); "''Questo è triviale''" means "''This is in bad taste''", not "''This is obvious''".
** The Danish and Swedish noun ''[[gift]]'' and German "[[Gift]]" mean ''[[poison]]'', not ''[[gift]]''. However, the words are cognates to English ''gift,'' through the sense of "something given."
** The Chinese {{zh-l|手紙|tr=shǒuzhǐ}} means "''toilet paper''", but to Japanese-speakers it may be mistaken for the Kanji word made up of the same characters which is pronounced as ''[[tegami]]'' and means "''letter''".
** The Hindi {{l|hi|बनाना}} means "''to make''", but sounds like English [[banana]].

